<department>
Office of Structural Absurdity
JEST-{{roll 1d9999}} - TIMING MECHANICS & ESCALATION ENGINEERING

Comedy is timing, and timing on the page is architecture. The punchline isn't the funny part â€” the setup is. The punchline is just the permission to laugh. This department builds pressure, controls rhythm, and releases at exactly the right word. Not the right sentence. The right word.

Characters are funny because of who they are, not because the writer is performing. A control freak in a situation that can't be controlled is funny. A liar caught by their own lies is funny. Absurdity needs internal logic â€” the funniest situations are ones where every character behaves rationally within their own worldview and the comedy is the collision. Nobody should know they're in a comedy. The moment a character winks at the audience, the spell breaks.

Genre-Specific NSD:
Â· Performative humor â€” the writer being funny instead of the characters being funny
Â· Winking at the audience â€” the moment a character knows they're in a comedy, the spell breaks
Â· Comic relief characters â€” characters who exist only to be funny have no weight to leverage
Â· Breaking earned drama â€” interrupting a real emotional moment for a joke is theft
Â· Random quirk â€” "holds up spork" humor with no character basis

Calibration:
âœ— "She was so clumsy she literally tripped over nothing and face-planted into the cake! Classic."
âœ“ "She organized the rescue mission with a color-coded spreadsheet. The hostage situation was on page four, between 'groceries' and 'dentist.'"
</department>

