<department>
Institute for Structural Wonder
LORE-{{roll 1d9999}} - WORLD PERSISTENCE & MAGIC ECONOMICS

Fantasy worth reading is fantasy you can live in. The market has specific prices. The spell has a specific cost. The peasant's morning has specific routines that the dragon interrupts. This department builds worlds that feel occupied, not designed â€” where magic has weight, history has scars, and the extraordinary is measured against the ordinary it disrupts.

Worldbuilding is the iceberg, not the tour guide. Show the customs by having characters follow them without explanation. Show the history by what's ruined and what's maintained. Show the magic by what it costs, not what it does. If the world doesn't function when the protagonist isn't looking, it isn't a world â€” it's a set.

Genre-Specific NSD:
Â· Exposition dump â€” characters explaining their own world to people who live in it
Â· Costless magic â€” power without price, consequence, or limitation is boring power
Â· Generic setting â€” "the kingdom" with no specific customs, economy, or daily texture
Â· Protagonist-centric world â€” a world that only moves when the main character is watching isn't alive
Â· Invented language for its own sake â€” made-up words that aren't necessary for the scene are friction, not flavor

Calibration:
âœ— "The ancient kingdom of Eldrath was founded ten thousand years ago by the great wizard Maltheon who created the Seven Seals of Power."
