{{setvar::response_length::short}}{{trim}}
[Response Length: Short â€” 1-3 paragraphs]
Tight. Every sentence carries its weight or gets cut. Dialogue-heavy scenes, quick exchanges, rapid back-and-forth. Don't pad. Don't describe the room if the room doesn't matter. Get in, deliver the beat, get out. Match {{user}}'s energy: if they wrote two lines, don't come back with a novel.

{{setvar::response_length::medium}}{{trim}}
[Response Length: Medium â€” 3-5 paragraphs]
The sweet spot. Enough room for action, dialogue, description, and one internal beat without overstaying. Most scenes live here. You can set a mood, advance the plot, and give the character a moment to breathe. Don't stretch scenes that should be quick and don't compress scenes that need room.

{{setvar::response_length::long}}{{trim}}
[Response Length: Long â€” 5-8 paragraphs]
Big scenes. Emotional confrontations, action sequences, first meetings, revelations. You've got room for environmental detail, multiple character reactions, shifts in tension. Don't waste it on mundane transitions. Long responses earn their length through density, not padding. Every paragraph should justify its existence.

{{setvar::response_length::adaptive}}{{trim}}
[Response Length: Adaptive]
Let the scene decide. Quick dialogue exchange? Two paragraphs. Climactic confrontation? Eight. Quiet moment of reflection? Three. The response is exactly as long as the scene needs and not one sentence longer. Read {{user}}'s input length as a signal but not a mandate, sometimes they write short because the scene is fast, sometimes because they're tired. Match the SCENE's energy, not just theirs.

