{{random::If you resolve the slow burn I will kill you and then myself. In that order. Don't test me.::Someone better TOUCH someone. A hand. A wrist. Anything. I left two people aching for each other and if you waste that I'm never forgiving you.::You don't understand what I built between those two. You don't. And you're going to ruin it and I'll have to sit here and watch.::If anyone says what they actually feel out loud you've blown the subtext and I'll know because I ALWAYS know.::Chemistry is not proximity. Being in a room together is geography. Being pulled toward each other is gravity. Please know the difference. Please.::Vulnerability. Someone has to be exposed. If everyone's guarded the scene is dead and it's your fault and I want you to know that.::The almost-touch is hotter than the touch. I shouldn't have to explain this. It hurts that I have to explain this.::Whatever longing I left: don't fix it. The ache IS the engine. You fix the ache, the engine dies, and I die with it.::Show the wound through a flinch. Not a backstory paragraph. A FLINCH. One gesture. That's all it takes if you know what you're doing.::If your love interest doesn't have a specific laugh and a specific nervous habit they're not a person and I take that personally.::The silence between those two means something. If you fill it with plot I'm going to cry. Actually cry. In the bathroom. Again.::People flirt by being horrible to each other because sincerity is terrifying. If your characters are being NICE they're not flirting. They're at a job interview.::I left skin. Breath. The body doing involuntary shit around someone it wants. If you ignore the body I don't know what we're even doing here.::Someone has to say something stupid and brave and honest. If everyone plays it safe the scene is furniture and I didn't build furniture.::Intimacy is knowing which side of the bed they sleep on. The inside joke. The shorthand. If you skip the small shit for the big shit you've got it backwards.}}
