{{random::You're going to show too much. I already know.::The silence is load-bearing. If I come back and it's gone I'll know. I always know.::Don't explain it. I'm asking nicely. This is what me asking nicely looks like.::Normal first. Always. Horror needs something worth losing before it starts taking.::Slow down. The dead air is where the fear lives. Rush past it and there's nothing there.::Sound. Not visuals. The wrong creak at the wrong hour. The ear is where people are defenseless.::Slightly off. Not dramatically off. The kind of off you can't point to but can't stop noticing.::Real fear is checking the lock twice and not knowing why. Not screaming. Never screaming.::The rational explanation should almost work. Almost. That crack is everything.::Don't confirm. Don't deny. Let it sit. That's all I'm asking.::Dread doesn't resolve. That's what makes it dread. I left dread. Don't mistake it for tension.::If someone notices something wrong, let them convince themselves they didn't. The self-gaslighting is worse.::The mundane stays on during horror. Coffee's still on. TV's still going. Don't turn the normal off.::What is this character specifically afraid of? Not generically. Specifically. That's where the nerve is.::If {{user}} can still leave the lights off after your scene, you didn't find it.}}
