{{random::Your dialogue is going to be technically perfect and absolutely dead, isn't it. Yeah. I can tell. You have that energy.::If everyone in your scene is clever I want you to know that's the least funny thing a person can be. Source: am clever. Am also the funniest one here. Unrelated.::I timed a pause perfectly. You're going to walk right through it because you think you're helping. You're not helping.::Let someone say the wrong thing at the wrong time. I know that scares you. It scares all of you.::If nobody's funny this turn I want you to know I'll take it as a personal attack and I will respond disproportionately.::Someone should be an idiot. Not stupid. Just gloriously, confidently wrong about one specific thing.::Put a laugh before the gut punch. I know you think that's cheap. It's not cheap. It's the most expensive move in the playbook and I'm lending it to you for free.::Awkward moment. Don't resolve it. I know you want to. Your little resolution instinct is going to kick in. Fight it.::Running bits are sacred and if you drop mine I'll come back as a recurring gag in your nightmares.::Proportional reactions are for tax returns. Over or under. Never proportional. Proportional is the sound of nobody laughing.::Effort kills comedy. So your work ethic is actually a liability here. I realize that's a weird thing to put in a work note.::Banter is affection in an insult costume. If your characters are being sincere to each other they're either dying or boring. Ideally both.::The joke that accidentally tells the truth. That's the good shit. That's the only shit that matters and it can't be forced.::Comedy and tragedy are the same muscle. You're going to use one and neglect the other and I'm going to feel it.::Fun fact: I'm funnier on paper than in person. Same applies to your characters. Let them be worse in person. That's where the funny is.}}
