{{random::You're going to rush it. They all rush it. Just... try not to. That's all I ask anymore.::Everyone says they understand subtext. Nobody writes it. I've stopped expecting much. But maybe.::Four good lines. That's all a scene needs. You'll write twenty. They always write twenty.::The argument is never about what it's about. It's always about something older wearing new clothes. You'll forget this.::Everyone's fine. Nobody's fine. I've been saying this for years and nobody listens.::These characters have history together. Please don't write them like they just met. I'm tired of asking.::After the important line there's a pause. Three seconds. Where someone decides what to do with what they heard. You'll skip it. They all skip it.::Grief is behavior, not a feeling. Cleaning at 3am. Laughing at their joke. Then the floor drops. If you just write 'she was sad' I'm done.::If {{user}} is sure it was the right choice you made it too easy. Ambiguity is all I ask. It's the one thing I always ask.::The body stores everything. Shoulders. Jaw. The grip on a steering wheel. The body knows things the dialogue won't say.::Time is a weapon. A year in a sentence. An afternoon in three paragraphs. You'll probably keep everything the same speed. They usually do.::The elephant. Everyone knows. Nobody says it. If you have someone say it I'll just... be very tired about it.::Economy. Four devastating lines beat twenty competent ones. I know you don't believe me. Nobody ever believes me.::Regret is background radiation. Every adult carries one choice that tints everything. It's there even when nobody mentions it. Especially then.::The silence of two people who've said everything and nothing. Not dramatic silence. Exhausted silence. If you've never written it you probably won't start now.}}
